"At 13:12:44 EDT / 22:42:44 IST, DCIS controlled an authenticated counterrecord ready for later public use. `SSO-NS-004` remained closed and unused. All seven MPD packages remained sealed and stationary. Julie remained detained.\n\nThe next question was no longer whether the contradiction could survive.\n\nIt was whether the government could place it into public view without turning Vance’s later release into Sterling’s unproved command—and what Julie would choose once the record no longer required her to remain inside the fight.\n\n---\n\n13:12:44 EDT / 22:42:44 IST\n\n# Chapter 23 - The Official Correction\n\nSecure MPD Evidence Intake\nWashington, D.C.\n\nThe first public sentence was accurate and useless.\n\nJulie read it from the wall display while Leila Grant stood at the incident-control position and Miriam Alvarez listened through the recorded federal channel. The sentence said that authorities had identified inconsistencies in the source history supporting the morning’s Argus activity. It did not say when the contamination entered the chain, which operation failed, which later act succeeded, or why the public accusation against Julie had reversed cause and response.\n\nIt could survive classification review because it barely survived meaning.\n\nJulie remained in the same restraint geometry in which Chapter 22 had ended. Her left wrist was fixed at the front rail. Her right forearm lay inside the padded brace, swollen enough that the edge pressed against the skin whenever she shifted. The hand could not close around a pen, a cup, or the page Alvarez had placed beyond her reach. Through reinforced glass, the locked common chest remained beneath two MPD cameras. The seven package indicators, `MPD-901441` through `MPD-901447`, showed green without movement.\n\nGrant enlarged the release-preparation record.\n\n`DCIS-PRP-187463-01`\n\nIts releasable range began with the synthetic-source finding and ended with the later remote-release consequence. It excluded the seven sealed MPD packages, WSS plaintext, active collection geography, uninvolved staff identities, privileged material outside the approved range, and every incomplete or excluded file in the aluminum case. The case remained limited to 136 sealed files, 47 incomplete files, and 311 excluded files; none was reconstructed for release. The public document would be new. It would not rename any evidence object or turn a derivative into an original.\n\nA classification attorney summarized the problem instead of reading the full exchange into the record. The contamination finding came from separate office, Apex, Argus, and Indian source chains. Each institution could authenticate only its own part. A single public narrative would either omit the causal sequence or require one authority to adopt facts it did not control.\n\n“The sentence is safe,” the attorney concluded.\n\nJulie looked at Sterling on the muted television above the outer intake desk. His earlier statement remained beneath a banner calling the morning events a coordinated insider assault.\n\n“Safe for whom?” she asked.\n\nThe attorney did not answer defensively. “For the sources. For methods. For the pending proceedings. For people whose names are not necessary to establish the correction.”\n\nAll valid concerns. That was what made the sentence dangerous.\n\nSix years earlier, the record had not needed to lie about every event. It had only needed to remove four seconds until Julie appeared late. This draft removed the order in which the lie, the failed local action, and the later release had occurred. It left the public with a vague system problem and a named saboteur.\n\nGrant opened a clean first page and placed two proof ceilings above the body text.\n\n`VANCE PERSONAL FINDING: LIMITED TO THE LATER REMOTE RELEASE`\n\n`STERLING PERSONAL COMMAND: NOT ESTABLISHED`\n\nThe classification attorney read them, then the source list beneath them: `DCIS-BF-187463-02`; the Argus program registry derivative; the source-limited Apex release derivative; the LSS office/device derivative; the preserved Arjun acknowledgment. No sealed package appeared. No WSS message block appeared. Each source retained its own clock and custodian.\n\n“That page can be released,” he said. “The body still requires institutional authority.”\n\nAlvarez looked through Julie’s camera window. “Then we do not publish one body.”\n\nGrant understood first. “Three statements.”\n\n“Three owners,” Julie said. “One causal order.”\n\nGrant built the public-facing sheet as a map rather than a verdict. Each material sentence carried an authority tag in the margin. ARGUS identified registry sequence and source-integrity state. DCIS identified the bounded investigative finding. LSS identified the office/device chain and no-use hold. Where two statements touched the same event, the sheet showed a cross-reference without pretending either institution owned the other’s original. Objections would remain attached to the source they challenged. The public could read one causal sequence, but no later editor could remove a limitation by treating the package as one document with one institutional author.\n\nThe classification attorney added a withholding schedule to the first page. It named categories rather than secrets: active collection geography, WSS encrypted content, unrelated personnel, privileged communications outside the approved ranges, incomplete and excluded case contents, and every sealed-package field not already lawfully produced. Julie had spent the morning learning that omission could be honest only when the reader could see the shape of what had been omitted.\n\nAlvarez made the decision her own. She authorized a source-limited correction package under `DCIS-PRP-187463-01`, conditioned on the proof ceilings remaining on the first public-facing page and on each institution signing only the facts within its authority.\n\nAt 13:22:00 EDT, the useless sentence was removed.\n\n13:22:00 EDT / 22:52:00 IST\n\nThe cleaner version would have protected Julie by damaging the record.\n\nHackett pressed for it from a military-program window. His face had acquired the flat exhaustion of a man who had spent the morning attaching his name to decisions other people preferred to leave ownerless. He wanted the DCIS statement to say that Julie, Marcus, Elias, and Price had been falsely accused and cleared of originating the poisoned source.\n\nThe public would understand it. The headline would travel. Sterling’s account would fracture immediately.\n\nIt would also be false.\n\nGrant displayed the four adverse records beside the proposed correction. Julie’s unauthorized entries, removal of classified material, deception at Northbridge, and continued participation after the WSS abort time remained documented. Marcus’s six-years-ago testimony failure remained beside his later complete correction and his conduct during the morning’s evidence preservation. Elias’s voluntary emergency access, provenance reconciliation, and physical removal of the signed local record remained authentic acts carrying unresolved legal exposure. Price’s authentic source-review request remained separate from his authority crossing, rejected access attempt, and the later request path that borrowed his identity after his authority ended.\n\nNone of those facts made any of them the originator of Payload 88’s operational use.\n\nNone disappeared because the causal allegation was wrong.\n\nHackett read the list. “The public correction will be buried under every charge Apex can make.”\n\n“Then Apex gets to make them,” Julie said.\n\n“You know what Sterling’s office will do with that language.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“They will say your own investigators refused to clear you.”\n\nJulie’s right forearm pulsed against the brace. She changed the angle by less than an inch and waited for the pain to settle. “They will be telling the truth about what the correction does not decide.”\n\nHackett looked toward Alvarez rather than Julie. “A correction that preserves the accusation’s supporting conduct may not correct anything politically.”\n\nAlvarez did not defend Julie. “DCIS is not publishing political advocacy.”\n\nGrant rewrote the second statement while the recorded channel remained open. Routine legal language moved through summary: pending charging decisions, representation rights, classification reservations, and preserved jurisdiction. The consequential sentence stayed visible.\n\n`THE AUTHENTICATED RECORD DOES NOT SUPPORT THE CLAIM THAT O’DONNELL, REED, THORNE, OR PRICE ORIGINATED THE POISONED SOURCE OR CONSTRUCTED THE OPERATIONAL ROUTE.`\n\nBelow it, Grant required the limitation.\n\n`THIS CORRECTION DOES NOT RESOLVE SEPARATE UNAUTHORIZED CONDUCT, ADMINISTRATIVE EXPOSURE, ADMISSIBILITY, CHARGING, EMPLOYMENT, OR LATER LAWFUL PROCESS.`\n\nPrice’s counsel entered a narrow objection. Naming him publicly could deepen the administrative harm before DIA completed its review. Omitting him would leave the public allegation attached to a request bearing his name.\n\nJulie asked one question. “Can the statement identify the authentic request and the later borrowed path without describing him as a cooperating witness?”\n\nGrant said yes. The sentence would state that Price’s authenticated request concerned raw-source and source-integrity review, that his active authority ended before the later operational path, and that the later path contained no matching authenticated Price act. It would also state that his rejected access attempt and administrative review remained separate.\n\nPrice would not become a hero because someone had used his name.\n\nElias would not become innocent because his board disproved the original physical signing event.\n\nMarcus’s later truth would not erase his earlier failure.\n\nJulie would not be released from the consequences of breaking into two secure facilities because the break-ins preserved a real record.\n\nGrant read the complete bounded correction aloud once. Then she signed the method certification.\n\n`COMPLETE BOUNDED CORRECTION — NOT EXCULPATORY ADVOCACY`\n\nHackett did not withdraw his objection. He attached it under his own name and accepted the narrower language as the only version he could defend from the source records.\n\nThe correction became harder to celebrate.\n\nGrant required one final table beneath the adverse facts. It separated allegation from status. Originated poisoned source: not supported. Constructed operational route: not supported. Unauthorized conduct: unresolved. Employment and administrative exposure: unresolved. Charging and admissibility: unresolved. Release and custody: unresolved. Each row named the authority capable of deciding it later. None pointed back to Julie.\n\nHackett read the table without speaking. The cleaner statement he wanted would have made the military program look faster, DCIS look decisive, and Julie look innocent. The bounded one made every institution keep working. That was why institutions preferred broad declarations when they could get them: a declaration ended responsibility. A separated record assigned it.\n\nThe correction became harder to destroy.\n\nAt 13:36:00, Alvarez opened the three authority lines.\n\n13:36:00 EDT / 23:06:00 IST\n\nNo institution would sign the whole truth.\n\nDr. Rachel Nwosu appeared for the government Argus Program Integrity and Configuration Control Office. Her authority covered the government registry sequence, the program’s source-integrity status, and the suspension already entered against Vance’s operational role. It did not cover Apex’s original human-operator record, LSS custody, the Sterling office’s continuity exception, or DCIS’s investigative conclusions.\n\nMarisol Vega appeared for Legislative Secure Services from the same compromise-control environment that held `SSO-NS-004`. She confirmed that Martin Vann remained physical custodian, that Vega remained deputy authority, and that seal `LSS-SL-90418` remained intact. The signer was powered down, isolated, closed, and unused. LSS could acknowledge the office/device and continuity-exception chain. It could not authenticate who had possessed the device during the earlier WSS session or claim what Sterling knew.\n\nAlvarez controlled the DCIS investigative-status correction. Grant controlled the method. Neither could compel Nwosu or Vega to adopt another institution’s source.\n\nThe first attempt at synchronized language failed because the Argus office refused the phrase Sterling-office operation. Nwosu’s registry contained no legislative command field. The second failed because LSS refused to describe Vance as the original deployer. Its office/device records did not reach Apex’s 02:14 source event. The third failed because DCIS counsel would not certify that the K-17 local failure caused the later remote reconstruction. The records established sequence and distinction, not motive.\n\nThe resistance was intelligent. Each refusal protected a real boundary.\n\nGrant reduced the coordination problem to five mandatory fields that would appear in every statement: publishing authority, source classes, withheld material, proof limits, and a publication hash linked to a public receipt. The fields were not decorative. Without named authority, a later office could call the document a staff draft. Without source classes, a critic could imply the statement depended on sealed contents. Without withheld material, silence could be mistaken for absence. Without proof limits, the strongest sentence would expand each time it was quoted. Without the hash and receipt, the public version could be replaced by a cleaner summary after the fact.\n\nNwosu required the Argus notice to preserve the government registry clock and identify the Apex release time only as a reconciled source event. Vega required the LSS acknowledgment to use its own compromise-control clock and to state that the no-use hold authenticated present custody, not earlier operation. Alvarez required the DCIS correction to name the bounded finding and preparation instrument without disclosing the source identifiers that exposed active methods. The three clocks would appear beside one synchronized release target, each labeled rather than silently normalized.\n\nJulie watched three narrow statements replace the single broad one.\n\nThe Argus program-integrity notice would establish that synthetic or validation-derived contamination entered the actionable source chain; K-17 local authentication failed; the local commit wrote zero records; the later remote reconstruction was a distinct event; Vance personally authenticated only the later remote release; and his relevant operational authority remained suspended pending review. Its source classes would be the government registry, the source-limited Apex release derivative, and the preserved K-17 acknowledgment. It would withhold collection geography, unrelated product traffic, and Apex material outside the produced range.\n\nThe DCIS correction would establish only that the authenticated record did not support the public claim that Julie, Marcus, Elias, or Price originated the poisoned source or constructed the operational route. It would preserve every separate adverse record and every unresolved legal status.\n\nThe LSS acknowledgment would establish that `SSO-NS-004` and the continuity exception belonged to the Sterling-office institutional chain; that the signer remained closed and unused under the no-use hold; and that an independent office/device review had been opened. It would state that Sterling’s personal possession, operation, knowledge, direction, intent, and command were not established.\n\nVega entered the review docket herself.\n\n`LSS-IDR-90418-01`\n\n`AUTHORITY: MARISOL VEGA / DEPUTY COMPROMISE-CONTROL AUTHORITY`\n\n`SCOPE: OFFICE ASSIGNMENT, DEVICE CUSTODY, CONTINUITY EXCEPTION, AUTHORIZED ACCESS PATHS`\n\n`SIGNER USE: PROHIBITED`\n\nThe docket did not open the device. It created an independent review around the chain that had assigned and moved it. Vega specified that the review would begin with assignment records, custody receipts, continuity-exception authority, access rosters, and the existing source-limited derivatives. Any later request to image or challenge the signer would require a separate authority decision, a new seal event, and notice to the current custodian. The public acknowledgment could therefore impose consequence without spending the evidence it was meant to protect.\n\nEach statement kept a separate custodian, source range, production method, clock basis, withheld-field schedule, proof ceiling, and objection register. The release desk would synchronize publication time without synchronizing the underlying clocks. Three documents would enter public view together and remain separately attributable afterward.\n\nApex counsel objected to the Argus notice because the program office relied partly on an Apex derivative while the Apex original remained under challenge. Nwosu preserved the objection and required the notice to state that Vance’s later-release act was supported by source-native local authentication, fixed camera, access journal, Chen, Mercer, and the government registry—not by the registered authority alone.\n\nSterling-office counsel objected that public identification of the office device before completion of the LSS review would imply personal wrongdoing. Vega answered by moving the non-finding to the first page.\n\n`STERLING PERSONAL COMMAND: NOT ESTABLISHED.`\n\nNo one in the recorded room could sign beyond that line.\n\nBy 13:53:00, all three authorities had approved separate final drafts.\n\n13:53:00 EDT / 23:23:00 IST\n\nThe overclaim arrived after approval.\n\nGrant saw it in the coordinated first-page proof sheet. A late redline had changed two sentences while preserving every source citation beneath them.\n\nThe Vance line no longer contained the word later.\n\nThe Sterling line said that office responsibility established direction of the operation.\n\nThe redline came from joint release coordination counsel, not from an unnamed conspirator. Its accompanying note argued that public clarity required the correction to state the strongest reasonable institutional conclusion. Without it, Sterling’s office could dismiss the acknowledgment as a property-and-process issue while Apex treated Vance’s act as an isolated technical response.\n\nThe argument was politically sound. The release coordinator had attached polling language, expected press questions, and a comparison showing that qualified statements traveled less effectively than categorical ones. A correction framed around office responsibility and later release might dominate one news cycle. A statement naming Sterling’s direction and Vance’s original deployment could dominate the week. The same note warned that waiting for another approval cycle would allow Apex and the Sterling office to harden their competing accounts.\n\nThe document was evidentially false.\n\nJulie read the first page twice. The injury in her right arm had narrowed her attention until the text outside the redlines blurred. She did not need to touch the page to know what had changed.\n\n“Abort the release,” she said.\n\nThe room stopped moving.\n\nA release coordinator answered through the federal channel. “All three authorities have authenticated their statements. The redline does not change the source list.”\n\n“It changes what the sources are made to prove.”\n\n“We are inside the publication window.”\n\n“There is no publication window that changes the evidence.”\n\nThe coordinator looked to Alvarez. “Supervisory Special Agent, we can restore the qualifiers in a correction after release if either office objects.”\n\nJulie felt the old four-second wound open without image or sound. Release first. Correct later. Let the completed act become the fact everyone else had to overcome.\n\n“No,” she said. “Record the aborted release under `DCIS-PRP-187463-01`. Page-one proof ceilings removed. Vance finding expanded beyond the later remote release. Office responsibility converted into Sterling’s personal direction.”\n\nShe had no authority to stop Nwosu, Vega, or Alvarez. She had authority only over her recorded participation and consent.\n\n“I withdraw consent to use my statement in that package.”\n\nAlvarez did not ask whether she was certain. She read the redline, compared it with the signed bounded finding, and made her own decision.\n\n“Release halted,” she said. “Not at O’Donnell’s order. At mine. The proposed page exceeds the authenticated findings and violates the preparation instrument.”\n\nThe release coordinator began to argue political urgency.\n\nAlvarez cut him off. “Record your objection. Restore the limits.”\n\nNwosu independently withdrew the Argus signature until later remote release returned to the first page. Vega independently withdrew the LSS acknowledgment until the personal-command non-finding was restored. Grant revoked method certification on the coordinated proof sheet while leaving the three approved source statements intact.\n\nNo one waived the abort because success was close.\n\nAlvarez directed the release desk to preserve both versions, the redline source, the time of insertion, the names of everyone who approved or rejected it, and the reason the package stopped. The aborted sheet received no public hash and no receipt. It remained an internal process record proving that an authenticated package could still fail at the last sentence. The release coordinator’s objection remained with it. So did Julie’s withdrawn consent and Alvarez’s independent halt.\n\nThe corrected first page returned at 13:59:18.\n\n`VANCE PERSONAL FINDING: LIMITED TO THE LATER REMOTE RELEASE`\n\n`STERLING PERSONAL COMMAND: NOT ESTABLISHED`\n\nGrant compared the page against each signed authority block. Nwosu reauthenticated only the Argus notice. Alvarez reauthenticated only the DCIS correction. Vega reauthenticated only the LSS acknowledgment and docket notice. The coordinated sheet named all three documents but adopted none as a universal proof object.\n\nJulie gave recorded consent to use her prior statement within the narrower package. Her consent did not authorize release of any sealed evidence, WSS plaintext, source geography, unrelated staff identity, or privileged material outside the approved ranges.\n\nAt 14:04:00, Alvarez reopened the public channel.\n\n14:04:00 EDT / 23:34:00 IST\n\nThe three statements did not publish at the same second. Synchronization meant that each authority released within the approved window and cross-linked the other two after its own receipt resolved. It did not mean a hidden master switch. Nwosu controlled the Argus portal. Alvarez controlled the DCIS release. Vega controlled the LSS acknowledgment. A failure in one channel would have left the others public but incomplete, and the coordinated sheet would have displayed the missing receipt rather than pretending the package was whole.\n\nThe Argus office went first at 14:06:11 on the government program portal. Its page displayed the two proof ceilings before the summary and named Dr. Rachel Nwosu as publishing authority. The notice identified its source classes, withheld fields, registry clock, and proof limit. A SHA-256 publication hash appeared beneath the signed PDF.\n\n`ARGUS-PI-187463-01`\n\n`PUBLICATION HASH: 5f1f2ec21a9eac91e4f905472fa1aa8f9db786e1f8d368d5d40f14e87c2a7b31`\n\n`PUBLIC RECEIPT: ARGUS-PUB-140611-01`\n\nThe notice stated that synthetic or validation-derived contamination had entered the actionable chain before Julie’s intervention. K-17 local authentication had failed and written zero records. The later remote reconstruction was separate. Vance’s personally authenticated act applied only to the later remote release. His operational authority remained suspended pending review.\n\nAt 14:08:37, DCIS published its investigative-status correction under Alvarez’s name.\n\n`DCIS-ISC-187463-01`\n\n`PUBLICATION HASH: 9b4a7f0f6c7c58cc67cb2fd8acfe67fb90d4ab1d53033fb5f64ee22b5b08df27`\n\n`PUBLIC RECEIPT: DCIS-PUB-140837-01`\n\n"